Machine Learning - Predicting Loan Interest Rate¶

So, we have 2 options:

  • Do the same thing we did for the last 2 parts: train multiple models (one per grade) and see how they perform.
    • Seeing how the data is distributed almost perfectly across the iridiscent colour spectrum, I expect pretty good predictive performance.
    • If we wanted to artificially inflate our performance, we could even create 1 model per subgrade, and it would get even less error.
  • OR!... we could do something different and actually learn something extra:
    • Create 1 model only, and see how it performs across all of the grades/subgrades.
    • Try to understand how each of the features contribute to the predicted rate, etc...

So, we're going to be build a single model. Heteroscedasticity is majorly expected to make a guest appearance. Let's see if it shows up.

Preparing the data¶

So, as we said before, now that we added grade and subgrade manually (after the cleaning and splitting pipelines in part 0 of the project), is, we need to do a tiny bit of additional encoding.

This encoding was not done in part 0 because I wanted to not include any of the other targets in each of the sprints datasets. In a real project, we would change the cleaning/splitting pipeline instead of doing this tiny manual change, but that takes a bit of rework, time, cognitive load, and the deadline is fast approaching. There is very little value in redoing this again from scratch now.

one-hot encoding our grades and subgrades¶

One of the things we should do, is encode the new info we included.

In [16]:
p_encode_grades = Pipeline(
    [
        (
            "onehot_grades",
            ce.OneHotEncoder(
                cols=["grade"],
                drop_invariant=True,
                return_df=True,
                use_cat_names=True,
                handle_unknown="ignore",
            ),
        ),
        (
            "onehot_subgrades",
            ce.OneHotEncoder(
                cols=["sub_grade"],
                drop_invariant=True,
                return_df=True,
                use_cat_names=True,
                handle_unknown="ignore",
            ),
        ),
        ("drop_1_grade", clean.ColumnDropper(["grade_G"])),
        ("drop_1_sub_grade", clean.ColumnDropper(["sub_grade_G4"])),
    ]
)

encoded_X_hyper = p_encode_grades.fit_transform(X_hyper)

encoded_X_train = p_encode_grades.fit_transform(X_train)

Predicting interest rate¶

In previous parts we have chosen, used and compared 4 classifiers (that worked with binary and multiclass labels):

  • XGBClassifier
  • Logisitc Regression
  • Random Forest
  • ExtraRandom Trees

This problem is a regression problem instead of a classification problem, so we will use and tune models that are the equivalent of those for. Just to see how they compare, and to give a sense of cohesion to the project.

I initially thought about not including Linear Regression as it seemed it will be too simple, but seeing how strongly grade/subgrade follow interest rate, I think even Linear Regression can get good results!

Let's see if my optimism is warranted!

So, we will be using and comparing these 4 regression models:

  • XGBRegressor()
  • ElasticNet()
    • We could use LinearRegression(), except that it's so simple it has no hyperparameters to tune. Instead of that, we will use a slightly more elaborate version of it called ElasticNet Regression, which has some hyper parameters to aid in l1 and l2 regularization.
  • RandomForestRegressor()
  • ExtraTreesRegressor()

In [20]:
def sprint4_tune_all_models():
    X = encoded_X_hyper
    y = y_hyper

    for model_name, candidate_provider in candidate_providers.items():
        print("training model:", model_name)
        study_name = f"sprint4_{model_name}"
        optuna_utils.create_optuna_study(
            study_name=study_name, allow_resume=True, direction="minimize"
        )
        objective = optuna_utils.build_objective_function(
            candidate_provider, X, y, scoring_function=mean_squared_error
        )
        optuna_utils.parallelize_optuna(
            study_name, n_processes=10, trials_per_process=2, objective=objective
        )


if run_entire_notebook():
    sprint4_tune_all_models()

@run
@cached_chart()
def sprint4_plot_performance():
    scores = {}
    for name in candidate_providers.keys():
        model = optuna_utils.get_study(f"sprint4_{name}")
        rmse = model.best_value ** (1 / 2)
        scores[name] = rmse

    scores = pd.Series(data=scores)
    plt.title("RMSE for the 4 chosen models")
    plt.ylabelel("error from interest rate")
    return sns.barplot(x=scores.index, y=scores)

Understanding feature importance¶

In [27]:
@cached_with_pickle()
def sprint4_get_feature_importances():
    feat_importances = {}
    for name in candidate_providers.keys():
        model = optuna_utils.get_best_model(f"sprint4_{name}")
        X = encoded_X_hyper
        y = y_hyper
        model.fit(X, y)
        importances = models_utils.feat_importance_from(model, encoded_X_hyper.columns)
        feat_importances[name] = importances

    return feat_importances


feature_importances = sprint4_get_feature_importances()


@run
@cached_chart()
def sprint4_plot_feat_importances():
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 4, figsize=(20, 20))
    for (names, importances), (row, col) in zip(
        feature_importances.items(), itertools.product(range(1), range(4))
    ):
        cax = ax[col]
        cax.set_title(names)
        feats = pd.Series(importances).sort_values(ascending=False)
        cax.set_xscale("log")
        sns.barplot(y=feats.index, x=feats, ax=cax, color="lightgrey")
    plt.tight_layout()
    return fig

Loading from cache [./cached/charts/sprint4_plot_feat_importances.png]

A few insights:

  • Just as expected, the top contributing features involve the grade columns (one-hot encoded).
  • The best performing model uses almost ALL grade columns before getting into any of the other ones.
  • The tiny differences between RandomForests and ExtRaForests seems to hint that they might have a similar workings underneath (they do!). But I am not sure this reasoning is valid/enough to make this statement for other models. Maybe it is just coincidence.

Next steps¶

This is the end of sprint 4.

In this sprint, we have have built models to predict the loan interest rate using regression algorithms.

We have seen how all 3 tree-based models perform relatively well, except for XGBRegressor which shows small signs of overfitting.

The performance of these regression algorithms is quite remarcable (as expected), since two of the features they can use are grade and subgrade. It would have been really hard to understand if they performed poorly.
